      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why TION Is a Bingo Powerhouse</h2>

      <p>Unlike shorter suffixes that merely extend words, -TION fundamentally changes your bingo calculus. With 4 tiles already committed to the ending, you only need 3 root tiles to hit 7 letters — the minimum for a bingo play worth 50 bonus points.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 The TION Bingo Math</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Holding T, I, O, N means you need just <span class="text-white font-medium">3 more tiles</span> for a 7-letter bingo. Common 3-letter roots that pair with TION: STA (STATION), MO (MOTION), NA (NATION), AC (ACTION), OP (OPTION), LO (LOTION), PO (POTION). That's 7+ ready bingos from one suffix hold.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Quick-Play TION Words for Tight Boards</h2>

      <p>When the board is congested, these shorter -TION words fit into compact spaces while still delivering respectable scores.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">ACTION</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">10 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">NATION</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">6 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">MOTION</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">8 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">POTION</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">8 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">LOTION</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">6 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">OPTION</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">8 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">RATION</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">6 pts</span>
        </span>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategic Value of Longer Suffixes</h2>

      <p>The -TION ending consumes more rack tiles than short suffixes like -ED or -ER, but this tradeoff works in your favour when you understand the bingo dynamics.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Fewer root tiles needed:</span> With 4 tiles in the suffix, you only need 3 root tiles for a bingo. This means less reliance on drawing perfect combinations — almost any 3 common consonants pair with TION.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Board reach advantage:</span> 8-letter TION words span further across the board, increasing your chances of landing on premium squares. A word like FRACTION can stretch from a Double Letter to a Triple Word Score.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Rack turnover speed:</span> Playing a 7-8 letter TION word replaces your entire rack, giving you a fresh draw. This is crucial in the mid-game when tile distribution matters most.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Predictable letter patterns:</span> T, I, O, N are among the most common tiles in the bag (6, 9, 8, 6 copies respectively). You'll naturally draw TION combinations more often than you'd expect.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Premium Square Interactions</h2>

      <p>With 8-letter TION words being common, you have excellent coverage of premium squares. The key is positioning the high-value root letters on multipliers while letting TION fill the remaining spaces.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ X on Triple Letter</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">FIXATION with X on TLS scores 42 points before bingo bonus. Position the high-value root letter on the multiplier, let TION fill naturally.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Span Triple Word Score</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">An 8-letter TION bingo that crosses TWS triples the entire word — pushing scores past 80+ points in a single devastating turn.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">When to Hold vs When to Break</h2>

      <p>The 4-tile investment in TION is significant. Here's how to decide whether to commit to the bingo hunt or break up the suffix for smaller plays.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">1-2 turns</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Max hold time</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">3 tiles</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Root letters needed</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">15+ pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Break threshold</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>If your remaining 3 tiles include letters like S, R, C, L, or A — hold for the bingo. If they're awkward consonant clusters (W, V, Q without U), break TION apart and play individual words. The 50-point bonus only justifies holding if you have realistic bingo prospects.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Summary</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🎯 Summary</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">The -TION suffix is your <span class="text-white font-medium">most efficient path to bingo plays</span>. With 4 tiles in the suffix and only 3 needed for the root, it offers the best ratio of rack investment to bingo probability. Over 1,500 valid TION words exist, the component tiles are common in the bag, and 8-letter words reach premium squares more reliably than shorter plays. Hold TION when your root tiles support it — break it when they don't.</p>
      </div>

